<br>
(2) is a key point. When the whole space-time expands it expands at zero speed, as literally nothing moves. Better, no observer in the space-time could observe this expansion, as any measure of distance would give the same value before, during and after the expansion (the sample meter &quot;grows&quot; together with any other object). If you have to move &quot;into&quot; the space-time, then you're moving, an observer can detect you motion, and Einstein's space-time can't allow for motions faster than light...<br>
